div.p:
We must not by any means flatter our selves concerning the black action of this day. 'Tis well known (and I wish it may be as well laid to heart) how great an abhorrence primitive Christians had of such execrable Crimes. We may easily finde Albinians, or Nigrians, or Cassians, that is, Mutineers and Rebels amongst you Romans;
                  Tertull.
                (says one who lived within less than 200 years of Christ:) but (says he) you shall never finde any of this seditious turbulent humour amongst us Christians.

Methinks we may see the Church, as Jerusalem, with Tears upon her cheeks, bitterly crying out, that our David who had set his affection so piously upon the House of God;
                  Fuller's Church-History. another Constantine, a truly nursing Father, who was never sensible of any loss to himself,


if thereby gain might redound to God; as our Historians so justly acknowledge of him. Methinks we cannot but see the Church lamenting that this Royal Patron of Religion and Learning was thus barbarously taken from us.
